history.content: Haven't done it!! I think it could be doable, as in my opinion 61C didn't really rely too much on 61b. One thing you might want to review/learn a bit is git. But it begs the question, why? Why not just take 61b over the summer?

children.subject: Thanks for the reply! I still might end up taking 61B but the material in 61C is more interesting and relevant to me.

I think you'll be fine doing that! I believe you'll have 3-4 weeks between Spring semester and 61c summer, so it wouldn't hurt to read up on the basics of Java syntax, review certain data structures through Java implementation, and read up on Big O.

I think 61C assumed we were familiar with time complexity and Java syntax(more similar to C than Python). It's possible your instructor might give you some convoluted data structures that were taught in 61b, but I doubt you'll have to implement them and answer difficult questions on their concepts. Worst case, you can just read up on that data structure or algorithm(like DFS and BFS).
Oh unfortunate. I think 61c would be a great class to take in the summer, vs 61B which would be more valuable with the 15 week schedule. Do what you gotta do!

It turns out that 61C is at the same time as another class I would like to take, so I will be taking 61B. I am wondering now how the lab format that is offered this summer differs from the regular course offerings in F/Sp sessions? I assume there are still in person exams? Are the lectures posted as videos? Thanks.

history.content: I am in 61A this semester and would like to take 61C this summer before 61B. I believe I do have programming experience equivalent to that in 9C but I am not sure how much 61C depends on or builds off the material in 61B. Has anyone done this and or have insight? Thanks.
